	<text>
		<body>
			<div>
				<pb facs="#facs_1" n="1"/>
				<p facs="#facs_1_tr_1">
					<lg>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_1">
                            <placeName ref="geo-2643743">London</placeName>, <date when="1948-10-27">27 October 1948</date>.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_2">My dear <persName ref="gnd-118777378">Raymond</persName>,</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_3">I am very sorry that you are not feeling</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_4">well and as I did not hear from you today, I am rather worried that</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_5">that you might be ill. I prepared the <orgName ref="gnd-37543-3">Warburgs</orgName> for a possible delay [in the matter of the Re...?]</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_6">I hope I have news from you to-morrow. - I spoke to Miss Pearson on the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_7">telephone; she was very nice and told me that she had had a letter</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_l">from you, but their stock of Academy Reports has shrunk to eight</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_10">copies. They [?] are not for sale and the <orgName ref="gnd-812629-X">Oxford Press</orgName> could not let us</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_11">have any. But she is willing to let us have two of her eight copies</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_12">which she will send to me. I think that that is quite generous under</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_13">the circumstances - it is surprising that they have such a small</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_14">number printed. She said that she would have more printed for us</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_15">next year. - I am going to send <persName ref="gnd-118801775">Theiler</persName> his offprint to-morrow, I</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_16">have arranged with <persName ref="gnd-116183853">Bing</persName> to-day that they will photostat the essay in</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_17">about a fortnight from the copy which I am getting through Dr. Schmid.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_18">Talbot is going to send you the Alline and the Wundt. I had to tell</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_19">him that I found the Alline, and he begged me to let him have it</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_20">bound before it was sent to you. He promised to have it bound at</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_21">once and to send both books off without delay. I think that it is</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_22">also in your interest to have the copy in a less vulnerable state.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_23">I had a long conversation with Billanovich to-day who is quite nice</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_24">in his enthusiastic devotion to Petrarch scholarship. However, if</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_25">his English were not so pittoresquely bad, he would be something of</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_26">an amiable bore. - I am going to see both Talbot and <persName ref="gnd-116183853">Bing</persName> again to-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_27">morrow, I have not yet asked Talbot about the Cassiodor for Devreeses,</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_28">as he was not in to-day. When I saw him on Monday I had not had your</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_29">letter yet. - Marion Carr (Cox) wants me to meet a Pole, named Heitman</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_30">who is, as she says, a student of mediaeval philosophy (or rather</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_31">something more advanced than a student) and who is going to Canada</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_32">on a grant of the Lady Davis Foundation. I do not know whether this</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_33">means that he is going to McGill. Shall I have a look at him and tell</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_34">you whether I think he might do as Assistant for you ? I think he</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_35">comes from Cracow. - I had a nice letter from Percy Dobell who regrets</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_36">very much that all the items I ordered from him are sold. He is going</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_37">to send me his catalogues and 'hopes that he will not again disappoint</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_l_13">me so badly! - Theiler's article contains a number of useful referen-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_l_41">ces. It make me also look at his 'Vorbereitung des Neuplatonismus'</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_42">I feel rather depressed by the great erudition with which he masters</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_43">the neoplatonic literature and feel that if he had been asked to do</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_44">the apparatus of sources and parallel passages, he would have 'shaken</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_45">it out of his sleeve' - It is a kind of reaction like the one when</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_46">I found in Paris the book by the blessed man (at the moment I cannot</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_47">recollect his name) who 'knew everything'. - <persName ref="gnd-123279933">Walzer</persName>'s visit on </l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_48">Friday night was a gruellig ordeal. He came at 8.30 and stayed till</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_49">12 midnight.</l>
					</lg>
				</p>
				<pb facs="#facs_2" n="2"/>
				<p facs="#facs_2_tr_1">
					<lg>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_1">He brought <persName ref="gnd-116183853">Bing</persName>'s letter (from which you gave me excerpts in your letter)</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_2">with him and was very upset about it. He complained he could not</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_3">give you any information as you cut him completely. Than he gave me</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_4">a long sob story about how he loved and admired you, how he suffered</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_5">from your going away from Oxford, how he had always longed to be of</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_6">every possible assistance to you, and how you had always treated him</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_7">so brusquely that he had never had any chance of showing his</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_8">wonderful feelings. He actually had tears in his eyes most of the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_9">time which did not make him more beautiful. There was very little</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_10">I could say, as he simply did not take in anything intended to show</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_11">him to himself in a different light. I dwelt mainly on the incident</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_12">which I had experienced myself (not wanting to give him the impression</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_13">that you had discussed all the conversations between you and him with</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_14">me in detail), viz. the story about the last Academy Report! But he</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_15">simply brushed it aside, it was like talking to a wall of cotton wool.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_16">I had arranged to be interrupted at 10 by Miss Brown (saying only that</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_17">I had a boring visitor who needed some prodding to be reminded of the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_18">time), but he outsat the interruption and got only going after she left</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_19">at 11.30. Miss <persName ref="gnd-120712016">Anscombe</persName> came in, returning from a party. She took</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_20">a violent dislike to him immediately and made no attempt to hide it,</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_21">but he talked blithely about <persName ref="gnd-118650130">Aristotle</persName> (when there were third people</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_22">in the room, he naturally spoke of impersonal matters). - One thing</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_23">emerged, viz. that Ross must have written to him proposing (of course</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_24">I do not know in what terms) the triumvirat in the editorship of the</l>
					</lg>
				</p>
			</div>
		</body>
